    "3) A Web API, or Web Application Programming Interface, is a specific type of API that is designed to be accessed over the web using HTTP protocols. It allows different software systems to communicate and interact with each other through web-based requests and responses.\n",
    "\n",
    "Differentiating between API and Web API:\n",
    "\n",
    "API (Application Programming Interface):\n",
    "- An API, in general, is a set of rules and protocols that specifies how software components should interact and exchange data.\n",
    "- APIs can be implemented in various forms, such as libraries, frameworks, protocols, or services.\n",
    "- APIs can be used for communication between different software components within the same system or between different systems.\n",
    "- APIs can be platform-specific or platform-agnostic, and they can use various communication protocols and data formats.\n",
    "\n",
    "Web API (Web Application Programming Interface):\n",
    "- A Web API is a specific type of API that is accessed over the web using HTTP protocols.\n",
    "- Web APIs are typically based on REST (Representational State Transfer) architectural style, which emphasizes stateless, client-server communication over HTTP.\n",
    "- Web APIs are widely used for exposing functionalities and data of web applications to external developers or services.\n",
    "- Web APIs use standard HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE) to perform operations on resources identified by URLs.\n",
    "- Web APIs commonly utilize data formats like JSON (JavaScript Object Notation) or XML (eXtensible Markup Language) for structuring and exchanging data.\n",
    "\n",
    "In summary, while API is a broader term referring to a set of rules and protocols for software communication, a Web API specifically refers to an API accessed over the web using HTTP. Web APIs are designed for web applications and utilize standard web technologies and protocols."
   ]
  },
